  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Easiest Coats We Carry" imageAlt="Chihuahua puppy being gently brushed during coat care" imageSrc={chihuahuaGrooming} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Here the Chihuahua wins outright. The smooth coat needs a weekly brush and the occasional bath; the long coat needs brushing 2 to 3 times a week and a tidy-up groom every couple of months. No mats, no monthly salon bill, no humidity drama: this is the lowest-grooming breed in our lineup alongside the smooth-coat Mini Dachshund.</p>
      <p>Both coat types shed lightly year-round, which is the honest trade against our low-shedding poodle crosses. Nail trims and the dental routine, with the tools already in your starter kit, matter more for this breed than anything to do with the coat.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Chihuahua Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Chihuahua puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={chihuahuaVet} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Chihuahua goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Chihuahua health points worth knowing: patellar luxation, a kneecap issue common to toy breeds; dental crowding, the breed's biggest lifelong issue, because a tiny jaw leaves no room for teeth, so the oral care routine starts on day one; low blood sugar in very young puppies, which regular small meals prevent; and the molera, a soft spot on the skull some Chihuahua puppies have, which usually closes with age and mostly asks for gentle handling.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the toy-breed food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Truth About Teacup and Micro Chihuahuas" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>No breed gets hit harder by "teacup" marketing than the Chihuahua, because it is already the smallest dog in the world. You will see "teacup," "micro," and "pocket" Chihuahua listings, often at a premium. We don't sell to that label. Dogs bred to be unusually tiny carry higher risks: fragile bones, severe dental problems, chronic low blood sugar, and shorter lives.</p>
      <p>A healthy Chihuahua at 1.5 to 3 kg already fits in a tote bag. If a seller promises a size below that and guarantees it, treat the promise as a warning, not a feature.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Teacup red flags</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Guaranteed adult weight below 1.5 kg',
            'No mention of the parents\' actual size',
            '"Teacup" or "micro" priced at a premium',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Chihuahua's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Chihuahua puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={chihuahuaSettling} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Chihuahua explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, warm and close. Tiny puppies chill easily under aircon, so a warm bed corner matters, along with a fixed feeding routine and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer, the single best investment against future yappiness; see <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

  <div id="reviews" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <Carousel
      heading="What Curious Tails Owners Say"
